               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate notBefore="1700" notAfter="1799">18th century, an earlier period (17th century) cannot be excluded.</origDate>
                     <ref target="#a3">Additional note 3</ref> suggests that the manuscript was related to the <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/ETH1274Betaes">Beta ʾƎsrāʾel</persName> community.
                     <bibl corresp="http://zotero.org/groups/358366/items/TD8PSEDC"><seg type="journalArticle"><!-- attributes from original bibl--></seg><ptr target="bm:Butts2013Reception"/><title level="a">Embellished with Gold: The Ethiopic Reception of Syriac Biblical Exegesis</title><title level="j">Oriens Christianus</title><author><t:forename xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Aaron Michael</t:forename><t:surname xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Butts</t:surname></author><date>2013</date><biblScope unit="volume">97</biblScope><biblScope unit="page">137-159</biblScope><citedRange unit="page">5-6</citedRange></bibl> indicates that, contrary to R. Cowley's claim 
                     (<bibl corresp="http://zotero.org/groups/358366/items/5P8JXIEB"><seg type="journalArticle"><!-- attributes from original bibl--></seg><ptr target="bm:Cowley1984Commentaries"/><title level="a">A Ge‘ez Document Reporting Controversy Concerning the Bible Commentaries of Ibn aṭ-Ṭaiyib</title><title level="j">Rassegna di Studi Etiopici</title><author><t:forename xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Roger W.</t:forename><t:surname xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Cowley</t:surname></author><date>1984</date><biblScope unit="volume">30</biblScope><biblScope unit="page">5-13</biblScope><note type="url">http://www.jstor.org/stable/41299680</note><citedRange unit="page">6</citedRange><citedRange unit="note">10</citedRange></bibl>) and to what may
                     appear at the first glance, the incipit on <locus target="#2r"/>has not been altered (e.g. with the aim of surpressing the Christain doxology, as it commonly happened to
                     Christian manuscripts 
                     acquired and customized by <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/ETH1274Betaes">Beta ʾƎsrāʾel</persName>). However, <ref target="#a3">Additional note 3</ref>, being a doxology considered
                     typical for <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/ETH1274Betaes">Beta ʾƎsrāʾel</persName>, appears to have been added later, in a different hand. Other features that may be indicative of 
                     the <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/ETH1274Betaes">Beta ʾƎsrāʾel</persName>'s ownership of the manucript have not been addressed yet.   
                  </origin>
                     <provenance>
                    The manuscript was acquired by <persName role="owner" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS1071dAbbadi">Antoine d'Abbadie</persName>
                      sometime between <date>1840</date> and <date>1848</date>.
                    </provenance>
                  <acquisition>The manuscript entered <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/INS0303BNF">Bibliothèque nationale de France</placeName> in
                    <date>1902</date>.
                    </acquisition>
               </history>
